    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Oct 17<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.—</date>
                    <salute>My dear Hooker</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I thank you heartily for your most kind congratulations about Horace, which rejoices us deeply.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p> 
                    <p>I happened to know of the reference to the work on Heliotropism in, I think, Olivers hand-writing.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> But I write now for the <hi rend="underline">chance</hi> of your having any or all of the 3 kind of seeds, <hi rend="underline">on next page</hi>: I want much to see how the seedlings, which are so peculiar break through the ground.—</p>
<p>Ever yours | Ch. Darwin</p> 
<figure type="diagram"> 
<p>Delphinium nudicaule</p>
<p>Ipomœa leptophylla</p>
<p>Megarrhiza Californica</p> </figure> 
<p>(These plants are mentioned by Asa Gray in New Edit of Bot. Text-Book p. 21, 22)<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>Do not write if you have not the seeds</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">4.1 Delphinium] ‘h’ <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">8.1 Do … seeds] <hi rend="italic">on verso, pencil</hi></note>
            </div>

            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the allusion to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1226.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Horace Darwin’s</ref> engagement, which was made public in October 1879 (<ref target="./DCP-LETT-12253.xml">letter from T. H. Farrer, 12 October 1879</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Horace was engaged to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1227.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Ida Farrer</ref> (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12253.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from T. H. Farrer, 12 October 1879</ref>).</note> 
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Hooker’s letter has not been found, and the work on heliotropism has not been identified. Oliver: <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3589.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Daniel Oliver</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><hi rend="italic">Delphinium nudicaule</hi> is red larkspur; <hi rend="italic">Ipomoea leptophylla</hi> is the bush morning-glory; <hi rend="italic">Megarrhiza californica</hi> is a synonym of <hi rend="italic">Marah fabacea</hi>, the California manroot. Gray had pointed out that the cotyledons of these three species developed in an unusual way (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3058.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">A. Gray 1879</ref>, pp. 20–2). See also <hi rend="italic">Movement in plants</hi>, pp. 80–4.</note>
        </div>
    
